What actually clicked once I stopped fighting React’s rendering model
I used to think useEffect was just the place you put code that needed to run "after render."
useEffect(() => {
fetchUser();
setLoading(false);
updateSomethingElse();
}, []);Empty array, done, ship it. That was my entire mental model for longer than I’d like to admit.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

One day I was reviewing a pull request from a senior engineer on my team, expecting to leave a couple of nitpicks and move on. Instead I found myself staring at a component with almost no useEffect calls at all, handling behavior I would have reached for three separate effects to build. No race conditions. No stale closures. No dependency array he was quietly ignoring warnings about.
I asked him about it, half expecting some clever library I hadn’t heard of. He just said, “Most of the time you don’t actually need an effect. You need to ask what you’re really synchronizing.”
That sentence rearranged something in my head that took years of Stack Overflow answers to almost, but not quite, get right.
Most developers use useEffect as a dumping ground for anything that happens after render. The ones who write React well use it for exactly one thing: synchronizing your component with something outside React.
Here’s what actually changed how I write components, the habits I wish someone had handed me on day one instead of letting me discover them one broken production bug at a time.
useEffect Is Not a Lifecycle Method
I came from a background where componentDidMount and componentDidUpdate made intuitive sense, and I quietly mapped useEffect onto that same mental shape. That mapping is the root of almost every bad effect I've ever written.
An effect isn’t “run this when the component mounts.” It’s “keep this external thing in sync with these values.” The moment I started reading my own dependency arrays as a description of what I was synchronizing, instead of a list I adjusted until the linter stopped complaining, effects that used to feel fragile started making sense on their own.
If You’re Calculating a Value, You Don’t Need an Effect
This was the single most expensive habit I had to unlearn.
// what I used to write
const [fullName, setFullName] = useState('');useEffect(() => {
setFullName(`${firstName} ${lastName}`);
}, [firstName, lastName]);// what it should have been the whole time
const fullName = `${firstName} ${lastName}`;Anything you can compute directly from props or state during render doesn’t belong in an effect. Every one of those unnecessary effects is an extra render cycle, a chance for the derived value to briefly go stale, and one more dependency array for future you to get wrong at 11pm before a release.
The Cleanup Function Isn’t Optional Housekeeping
For a long time I treated the return function inside an effect as something you add only when linked to a subscription or an interval, mostly to satisfy a linter warning. What actually changed my thinking was watching a subtle bug where a fetch from a previous render resolved after a component had already re-rendered with new props, silently overwriting fresher data with stale results.
useEffect(() => {
let ignore = false; fetchResults(query).then((data) => {
if (!ignore) setResults(data);
}); return () => {
ignore = true;
};
}, [query]);The cleanup function isn’t housekeeping. It’s how you tell React which version of the effect is still allowed to matter. Skip it on anything async and you’re one fast typist away from a race condition that will pass every manual test and still ship broken.
One Effect, One Reason to Change
I used to write effects the way I wrote functions early in my career, cramming everything related to “stuff that happens on mount” into a single block because it felt tidier than scattering it across the file.
// one effect doing three unrelated jobs
useEffect(() => {
document.title = pageTitle;
const sub = subscribeToUpdates(handleUpdate);
logPageView(pageTitle);
return () => sub.unsubscribe();
}, [pageTitle]);Splitting that into three separate effects, one for the document title, one for the subscription, one for analytics, felt unnecessarily verbose the first time I tried it. It stopped feeling that way the first time I needed to change the subscription logic and could do it without rereading two unrelated concerns crammed into the same block. Each effect having a single reason to change is the same argument for small functions, applied to a part of React most people never think to apply it to.
Custom Hooks Are Where Effects Go to Stop Repeating Themselves
The habit that saved me the most time, once I actually built it, was noticing when the same effect shape showed up in three different components and pulling it into a custom hook instead of copy-pasting it a fourth time.
function useDebouncedValue(value, delay) {
const [debounced, setDebounced] = useState(value); useEffect(() => {
const timeout = setTimeout(() => setDebounced(value), delay);
return () => clearTimeout(timeout);
}, [value, delay]); return debounced;
}Once that logic lives in one place, fixing a bug in it fixes it everywhere at once, instead of hunting down four slightly different copies that have quietly drifted apart over six months of separate edits by separate people.
The Short Version
Senior engineers don’t write fewer bugs with useEffect because they've memorized more edge cases. They've internalized a narrower, more honest question before reaching for it at all: what am I actually synchronizing, and does it genuinely live outside React's own rendering model.
Most of the time, once you ask that question honestly, the effect you were about to write quietly disappears, and the component gets simpler for it. That question cost me years to start asking automatically. I’m hoping it costs you considerably less.
